%%TITLE
Young adult patients with squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue strongly express p16 without human papillomavirus infection.
%%ABSTRACT
Long-term smoking and drinking are known to contribute to the onset of tongue cancer (TC). However, the increasing incidence of TC in younger adults has been suggested to be associated with other factors.The present study investigated the relationship between TC and human papillomavirus (HPV) infection.Clinical records and surgically resected specimens from 86 patients (<40-years-old, nâ€‰=â€‰12; â‰¥40-years-old, nâ€‰=â€‰74) with TC were analyzed. Strong nuclear and cytoplasmic p16 staining was considered positive. HPV DNA (high-risk subtypes: 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 52b, and 58; low-risk subtypes: 6 and 11) was detected using consensus primer-mediated polymerase chain reaction.Strong p16 expression was observed in 10 (11.6%) patients. HPV DNA was detected in 9 (10.5%) patients (high-risk subtypes, nâ€‰=â€‰2; low-risk subtypes, nâ€‰=â€‰7). Strong p16 expression was observed more frequently among younger adults than among older adults (33.3% vs. 8.1%; pâ€‰=â€‰.045). p16 staining did not correlate with the detection of HPV DNA (correlation coefficient, 0.113; pâ€‰=â€‰.300).In TC, p16 expression was not associated with HPV infection, suggesting that it may be caused by a different mechanism.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patients
The clinical records of 86 Japanese patients (<40-years-old, n 12; 40-years-old, n 74), treated for TC at our institu- tion between 2001 and 2015, were analyzed. Tumors origi- nating from the base of the tongue were excluded. The cohort comprised 57 men and 29 women, with a mean age at diagnosis of 60.2 (range: 23–96) years. Smoking status was confirmed in 82 patients, including 47 (57.3%) who were smokers or ex-smokers. Alcohol consumption was also confirmed in 81 patients, including 39 (48.1%) who were current drinkers or ex-drinkers.
The 86 patients had squamous cell carcinomas (SCCs), staged according to the 2009 Union for International Cancer Control Tumor-Node-Metastasis classification. Positive lymph nodes were defined as nodes detected on computed tomography and/or magnetic resonance imaging and 18F-fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomography. Of the 86 patients with TC, 37 (43.0%) had Stage I disease, 13 (15.1%) had Stage II disease, 13 (15.1%) had Stage III disease, and 23 (26.8%) had Stage IV disease.
IHC staining
Paraffin-embedded tissue sections were used for IHC stain- ing using the CDKN2A/p16INK4a antibody (EPR1473) (dilution 1:200; Abcam, Cambridge, UK) and an automated Bond Max stainer (Leica Biosystems, Wetzlar, Germany). p16 staining intensity was scored as 0 (negative), 1 (weak nuclear staining), or 2 (moderate to strong nuclear and cytoplasmic staining) (). According to the
classification proposed by Orita et al. [], scores of 0 or 1 were considered negative and 2 was considered positive.
HPV DNA testing
HPV DNA was detected using consensus primer-mediated polymerase chain reaction (PCR) assays. DNA was extracted from paraffin-embedded tissue sections using the QIAamp DNA Micro Kit (QIAGEN, Valencia, CA) and quantified using a NanoDropVND-1000 spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Wilmington, DE). PCR was performed with reference to the TaKaRa PCR Human Papillomavirus Typing Set (Takara Bio, Tokyo, Japan). The following pri- mers were used:
High-risk forward primer: 50-TGTCAAAAACCGTTGTGTCC-30 Low-risk forward primer: 50-TGCTAATTCGGTGCTACCTG-30
Consensus primer: 50-GAGCTGTCGCTTAATTGCTC-30
The consensus primer was fluorescently labeled. HPV DNA (high-risk subtypes: 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 52b, and 58; low-risk subtypes: 6 and 11) was detected using these primers (Sigma- Aldrich, Tokyo, Japan). The PCR products were analyzed using an ABI PRISMV310 Genetic Analyzer (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA) with GeneScan and GeneMapper software (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA).
Treatment
Although treatments were chosen at the discretion of the attend- ing physician, all 86 patients underwent surgical resections. Additional treatments included: Stage I: surgery only (n ¼ 32), neoadjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 2), and adjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 3); Stage II: surgery only (n ¼ 9), postoperative radiother- apy (n ¼ 1), neoadjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 1), adjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 1), and neoadjuvant and adjuvant chemo- therapy (n ¼ 1); Stage III: surgery only (n ¼ 2), preoperative radiotherapy (n ¼ 1), neoadjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 5), and neoadjuvant and adjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 5); and Stage IV, neoadjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 12), adjuvant chemotherapy (n ¼ 1), postoperative chemoradiotherapy (n ¼ 1), neoadjuvant

and adjuvant chemotherapy (n 7), neoadjuvant and postoper- ative chemoradiotherapy (n 1), and neoadjuvant chemother- apy and postoperative bioradiotherapy (n 1). The chemotherapy regimens mainly comprised cisplatin or nedapla- tin and 5-fluorouracil, with the occasional inclusion of docetaxel. Tegafur/gimeracil/oteracil was sometimes administered as a sub- stitute for these agents, according to the patients’ age, disease stage, and performance status. In instances where the tumor did not exhibit a complete response or had recurred following initial treatment, additional treatments were administered. Patients were followed until their death or their last clinical evaluation (range: 1–140 months; mean: 37.6 months). During follow-up, 37 patients (43.0%) showed recurrence after the initial surgical treatment; loco-regional recurrence was observed in 15 cases (17.4%), 20 (23.3%) had neck metastasis, and 12 (14.0%) had distant metastasis.
Statistical analyses
Differences in baseline characteristics were assessed using Fisher’s exact test. Survival was defined as the time interval between the date of diagnosis and the date of death or last follow-up. Survival was estimated using the Kaplan–Meier method and compared using the log-rank test; patients lost to follow-up were censored. p < .05 was considered statistic- ally significant.
The study protocol was approved by the Institutional Review Board of Okayama University (Okayama, Japan). All patients were Japanese and provided written informed con- sent prior to treatment.
